	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Many Alarm Clocks</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/sy-safransky">Sy Safransky</a></li><li><a href="/issues/164">July 1989</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p class="dropcap">Running in the morning &mdash; thinking, as usual, of how I might improve myself, live closer to my feelings, devote myself more completely to God &mdash; I&rsquo;m stopped by two women, who want directions to some church. Jolted from my reverie, annoyed that they&rsquo;ve asked <em>me</em> rather than someone <em>walking</em> by, I tell them exasperatedly I don&rsquo;t know. They thank me politely; I run on.</p>

<p>It takes a minute for the irony to catch up with me, like a waiter chasing me with the unpaid bill: I was too busy thinking about God to help these women on their way to Him.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Numbers call to me. The phone rings. I&rsquo;m surrounded by letters, manuscripts, bills. The work is important, but it&rsquo;s just as important not to lose myself in the work, in the higher realms of efficiency, in my little myth of progress. How easy to be a busy man: to sacrifice myself on the altar of accomplishment; to light the incense and chant the mantra of success &mdash; not for money or glory, but success nonetheless. Theodor Storm: &ldquo;I felt that tiny insane voluptuousness,/Getting this done, finally finishing that.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t want to set one moment against another, this moment against that moment, the present against the past. Am I better now &mdash; better than I was then? Does she love me more than she loved him? Today, on my forty-fourth birthday, I was determined to do at least as many push-ups, run at least as far, as I did last year. Oh this chase! Murray Mednick: &ldquo;Time, the eternal blow job; you never come; she never lets go.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Wandering through the house at night, as I wander through my feelings, never quite at home. <em>Come in. Sit down and stay a while.</em></p>

<p><em>Well, I&rsquo;ll come in, </em>I say,<em> but I can&rsquo;t stay for long.</em></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><a href="/contributors/deena-metzger">Deena Metzger</a>: &ldquo;We can only heal so much. Some of what is broken in me will always be broken. Some grief is irreparable.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>I didn&rsquo;t save the world. I drank too much coffee. The trees were nearly dead before I noticed.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Once an hour, the beeper on my watch goes off. I use it to remind me to pause and remember, if only for a moment; to draw back the veil, and look at the One who looks back, unblinking.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Gurdjieff: &ldquo;A man may get awakened by an alarm clock. But the trouble is that a man gets accustomed to the clock far too quickly. He ceases to hear it. Many alarm clocks are necessary, and always new ones.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>This day is Yours. I thought my lists made it mine, but I was mistaken.</p>

<p>What do these words make mine?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Early in the morning, I make time to be alone. I don&rsquo;t call it meditating or praying. I call it closing my eyes and feeling my way across a narrow ledge. I call it dropping like a stone into the depths. There I&rsquo;m reminded nothing is what I think it is. Joy is real. Everything lives.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Wanting to be naked: nothing between me and my intention. Not this fear, this armor of propriety, the weight of the past upon my soft skin.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Ramakrishna: &ldquo;One must seek God as a drowning person seeks air.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Do You test my faith, or do I test Yours?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Like a child, I see how far I can turn from You, abandon You completely, before You remind me You&rsquo;ve never left. Do Your reminders seem harsh? How many do I ignore? You whisper to me, but I sleep. You come to me in a dream. I wake in the dark, cursing the alarm.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>In the shower, the shampoo bottle slips and hits my foot. It hurts. But I don&rsquo;t take the time to bend down and rub it, the way I would for a child. I&rsquo;m in too much of a hurry, and it&rsquo;s a distant little pain, easy to ignore.</p>

<p>Later, at my desk, I&rsquo;m scribbling out checks for Oxfam, Amnesty, Seva. These modest donations, I reason, are the least I can do. But I&rsquo;m still in a hurry, annoyed at the time it takes to deal with the world&rsquo;s pain, too.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Do the seasons hurry? Does the Earth turn more quickly because someone, somewhere, is impatient for the dawn? I can&rsquo;t rush my seasons, or the dawn in me of understanding.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Offhandedly, I joke with a friend when she mentions how lonely she&rsquo;s been. Later, I&rsquo;m amazed I could have been so insensitive. It isn&rsquo;t what I said; it&rsquo;s that I didn&rsquo;t pause to really hear what <em>she</em> said.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;m fully present, or I&rsquo;m not. The moment doesn&rsquo;t come again. I don&rsquo;t make up for it, like catching up on missed sleep or the lunch I skipped.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>I hide behind being busy, pretending there isn&rsquo;t enough time. Time for what? To remember who I really am? I deny my radiance, my brokenness. I confuse my life with the lines I&rsquo;m reading, with the dog-eared script.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>If truth is an arrow, pain is the bow. <em>True, true,</em> I say, as the arrow hits home. God arrives all at once, the air sighing around Him.</p>
														</div>


				
